%spark2.pyspark

# As we have audio features from spotify, we will select all related features for 'Rock' and 'Rap/HipHop'

track_genres = spark.sql("select artist, title, danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechiness, acousticness, liveness, valence, tempo, time_signature, genre from tracks where genre in ('Rock', 'Rap/Hip-Hop', 'Pop')")

track_genres.count()

%spark2.pyspark

# Now we can use describe() to see some stats of our data

track_genres.describe()

msg.data: DataFrame[summary: string, artist: string, title: string, danceability: string, energy: string, key: string, loudness: string, mode: string, speechiness: string, acousticness: string, liveness: string, valence: string, tempo: string, time_signature: string, genre: string]

paragraphs.text:
%spark2.pyspark

# This is a pipeline for extracting and assembling our features vector

from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler, StringIndexer

dataset = track_genres

stages = []
label_stringIdx = StringIndexer(inputCol="genre", outputCol="label")
stages += [label_stringIdx]
numericCols = ["danceability", "energy", "key", "loudness", "mode", "speechiness", "acousticness", "liveness", "valence", "tempo", "time_signature"]
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=numericCols, outputCol="features")
stages += [assembler]

pipeline = Pipeline(stages=stages)
pipelineModel = pipeline.fit(dataset)
dataset = pipelineModel.transform(dataset)
z.show(dataset)

%spark2.pyspark

# Now we will split our data with %70 / %30 for training and test sets

(trainingData, testData) = dataset.randomSplit([0.7, 0.3], seed=100)
print(trainingData.count())
print(testData.count())

##Fit and Evaluate Models
- Logistic Regression
- Decision Tree Classifier
- Random Forest Classifier

Fit and Evaluate Models

  • Logistic Regression
  • Decision Tree Classifier
  • Random Forest Classifier

paragraphs.text:
%md

#### Logistic Regression

%spark2.pyspark

# Now with label and features columns we are training a logistic regression model for our data

from pyspark.ml.classification import LogisticRegression

# Create initial LogisticRegression model
lr = LogisticRegression(labelCol="label", featuresCol="features", maxIter=10)

# Train model with Training Data
lrModel = lr.fit(trainingData)

%spark2.pyspark

# Now let's calculate the predictions for testData part

predictions_lr = lrModel.transform(testData)
predictions_lr.createOrReplaceTempView("predictions_lr")

%spark2.sql

-- select title, genre, label, prediction from predictions

select genre, sum(correct) as correct, sum(incorrect) as incorrect from (
select title, genre, label, prediction, case when(label==prediction) then 1 else 0 end as correct, 
case when(label!=prediction) then 1 else 0 end as incorrect
from predictions_lr
) group by genre order by 1,2

msg.data:

paragraphs.text:
%spark2.pyspark

# We will use BinaryClassificationEvaluator for evaluating our model

from pyspark.ml.evaluation import BinaryClassificationEvaluator

# Evaluate model
evaluator = BinaryClassificationEvaluator(rawPredictionCol="rawPrediction")
evaluator.evaluate(predictions_lr)
